azio, Italy":"Roma, Lazio, Italië","Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Roma, Lazio, Italië","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italië","Italy, Italy":"Italië"},"en":{"1125?–1157":"1125–1157","1124–Male":"1124–Deceased","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1135–1210":"1135–1210","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","1153–1205":"1153–1205","–1197":"–1197","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1098–1160":"1098–1160","1097–1160":"1097–1160","about 1150":"1150","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","1205":"1205","1313":"1313","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1125?":"1125","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1210":"1210","1100":"1100","about 1135":"about 1135","Europe":"Europe","Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italia":"Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italy","Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Lazio, Italy","Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy","Italy, Italy":"Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]},{"name":"di","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Diana   and   Diane ."],"variants":[{"name":"Diana","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]},{"name":"Diane","meanings":["form of   Diana  , now also widely used in the English-speaking world. It was especially popular among the Renaissance aristocracy, who loved hunting and were therefore proud to name their daughters after the classical goddess of the chase."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecilia di Medania was born in 1125, in Roma, Lazio, Italy, her father, Conte Roberto di Medania, was 27 and her mother, Giuditta di Buonalbergo, was 28. She married Rinaldo d'Aquino in 1150, in Italy. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1157, in Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1125?–1157":"1125–1157","1124–Male":"1124–Surnud","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1135–1210":"1135–1210","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1153–1205":"1153–1205","–1197":"–1197","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1098–1160":"1098–1160","1097–1160":"1097–1160","about 1150":"1150","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","1205":"1205","1313":"1313","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1125?":"1125","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1210":"1210","1100":"1100","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Europe":"Europe","Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italia":"Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Itaalia","Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Lazio, Itaalia","Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Roma, Lazio, Itaalia","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Itaalia","Italy, Italy":"Itaalia"},"fi":{"1125?–1157":"1125–1157","1124–Male":"1124–Kuollut","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1135–1210":"1135–1210","1135–Female":"1135–Kuollut","1153–1205":"1153–1205","–1197":"–1197","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1098–1160":"1098–1160","1097–1160":"1097–1160","about 1150":"1150","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","1205":"1205","1313":"1313","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1125?":"1125","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1210":"1210","1100":"1100","about 1135":"noin 1135","Europe":"Europe","Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italia":"Castello, Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italia","Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Lazio, Italia","Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roma, Roma, Lazio, Italia","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italia","Italy, Italy":"Italia"},"fr":{"1125?–1157":"1125–1157","1124–Male":"1124–Décédé","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1148–116